    "title": "Geopolitiks Snacks — April 30, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-30",
    "tags": ["China AI theft", "AI exports", "Taiwan sanctions", "UK AI sovereignty"],
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 30, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🕵️ The White House accused China of industrial-scale AI theft and turned distillation into a foreign-policy file\n\nWhat used to be a model training shortcut is now being briefed like counterintelligence.\n\n- **The accusation:** Reuters reported on April 23, 2026 that the White House said it had information showing foreign entities, mainly based in China, were conducting deliberate, industrial-scale campaigns to distill U.S. frontier AI systems.\n- **The diplomatic timing:** the memo landed just weeks before a Trump-Xi summit in Beijing, and China's foreign ministry responded by urging Washington to drop its bias and promote scientific and technological exchanges instead.\n\n*The model war has now fully merged with the spy memo genre.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters on White House accusations](https://www.streetinsider.com/Reuters/White%2BHouse%2Baccuses%2BChina%2Bof%2Bindustrial-scale%2Btheft%2Bof%2BAI%2Btechnology/26356704.html) | [Defense One summary](https://www.defenseone.com/threats/2026/04/china-steal-ai-models/413103/)\n\n---\n\n## 📦 Washington is now trying to export the entire U.S. AI stack, not just the software layer\n\nAmerica's AI strategy is increasingly simple: package the whole stack, brand it as trusted, and ship it abroad before someone else does.\n\n- **The program:** On April 1, 2026, the Commerce Department opened proposals for the American AI Exports Program, inviting industry-led consortia to submit full-stack AI export packages through June 30.\n- **What full-stack means here:** Commerce explicitly wants offerings that combine AI hardware, data pipelines, models, systems, financing support, and export-control engagement, all aligned with U.S. national security and foreign policy objectives.\n\n*Industrial policy has officially become a product bundle.*\n\n**Sources:** [Department of Commerce Begins Inaugural Call for Proposals for American AI Exports Program](https://www.trade.gov/press-release/department-commerce-begins-inaugural-call-proposals-american-ai-exports-program) | [Federal Register notice](https://www.trade.gov/sites/default/files/2026-04/American_AI_Exports_Call_for_Proposals_Federal_Register_Notice_%2801_Apr_2026%29.pdf)\n\n---\n\n## 🚫 Beijing slapped export controls on seven EU entities over Taiwan arms sales\n\nSemiconductor diplomacy was apparently not tense enough, so dual-use controls are now being used to discipline Europe too.\n\n- **China's move:** China's Commerce Ministry said on April 24, 2026 that seven EU entities were being added to its export control list, banning exporters from sending them dual-use items and prohibiting any overseas transfer of such items originating in China.\n- **The stated reason:** Beijing said the targeted entities had been involved in arms sales to Taiwan or collusion with Taiwan, while insisting the measures were aimed at a small set of military-linked entities and would not affect normal China-EU trade.\n\n*Taiwan remains the issue that keeps turning trade paperwork into geopolitical signaling.*\n\n**Sources:** [China's Commerce Ministry statement](https://www.mofcom.gov.cn/syxwfb/art/2026/art_b5216a7d5c3a4b82bb67482c44b3be18.html) | [Reuters on the move](https://uk.marketscreener.com/news/china-bans-dual-use-items-exports-to-7-european-entities-over-taiwan-arms-sales-ce7f59dfd98ef225)\n\n---\n\n## 🇬🇧 Britain is talking about AI sovereignty with a hardware plan and a geopolitical tone shift\n\nThe UK has moved from \"we host good labs\" to \"we need leverage in the AI stack before someone else decides our future for us.\"\n\n- **The message:** In a speech published April 28, 2026, UK Technology Secretary Liz Kendall argued that control over chips, compute, and AI is now fundamental to economic, energy, and defence security.\n- **The concrete step:** the government said it will develop a UK AI hardware plan to secure capability in chips and semiconductor technologies, while pushing a more muscular strategy around domestic AI companies and coordination with allies.\n\n*Everyone says they do not want isolation; everyone is also quietly counting their chips.*\n\n**Sources:** [Britain must secure greater control and leverage over AI](https://www.gov.uk/government/news/britain-must-secure-greater-control-and-leverage-over-ai-to-protect-our-national-security-in-fractured-world) | [GOV.UK press release](https://www.gov.uk/government/news)\n"
  }
]
